WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:05.040
With your Python environment set up and necessary libraries installed,

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:08.560
you're now poised to kick off your actual Python project.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:15.120
Most data science projects begin with data, so in this segment we'll demonstrate how to

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:20.320
effortlessly download a dataset using the PydyTuesday Python library.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:26.559
The datasets we will focus on reside on the PydyTuesday GitHub repository.

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:31.920
This repository is an incredible resource for exploratory data science,

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:34.400
with a brand new dataset added every week.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:40.400
For our example, let's grab a dataset posted in May of 2025

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:43.279
that dives into water quality at Sydney beaches.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:50.160
When you click on the dataset name, you'll see a Python code snippet with precise instructions

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:53.040
for using the PydyTuesday library to download it.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:59.759
Let's simply copy this snippet and paste it into a new Python script in Positron,

00:00:59.759 --> 00:01:02.480
which we'll name WaterQuality.py.

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:09.199
In addition to the PydyTuesday library, we'll also need to import the Pandas library.

00:01:09.199 --> 00:01:13.760
This will allow us to read our downloaded dataset directly into our Python environment.

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:20.720
One of Positron's great features is the ability to run your Python code line by line.

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:27.519
Simply place your cursor on a line and repeatedly press Command-Enter or Control-Enter.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:34.320
After importing both the PydyTuesday and Pandas libraries, we'll run the code on line 5.

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:37.760
This will download the Sydney water quality data

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:42.080
and its associated files directly into your project's working directory.

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:49.360
Now that the data is in our project, let's use the readCSV function from the Pandas library

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:54.800
to load it as a data frame and assign it to a variable we'll call WaterQuality.

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.080
And just like that, you'll see the WaterQuality variable appear in your variables pane.

00:02:00.639 --> 00:02:04.480
With Positron, you can inspect this data instantly.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:08.880
Just click the data frame icon, which will bring up the data visualizer.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:14.880
Here you can explore the raw data, view various summary statistics for each column,

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:17.199
and get a quick overview of your dataset.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:21.360
Now that you've successfully read in your WaterQuality data,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:23.199
you are ready to start analyzing.

00:02:23.839 --> 00:02:26.800
Whether you want to create stunning visualizations,

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.000
build insightful tables, or try out that new modeling technique you've been meaning to learn,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.080
the sky is truly the limit.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:38.800
Just remember to have fun and enjoy every step of your Python learning journey.

